  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Scrum (Essentials)&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Purpose&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;>&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;>Scrum is a framework structured to support complex product development. This practice&#xD;
    contains the definition of Scrum according to the Scrum Guide by Ken Schwaber and Jeff Sutherland.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Scrum&#xD;
    consists of Scrum Teams and their associated roles, events, artifacts, and rules. Each component within the framework&#xD;
    serves a specific purpose and is essential to Scrum’s success and usage.&lt;/font>&lt;/font>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Overview&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Scrum (n): A framework within which people can address complex adaptive problems, while productively and creatively&#xD;
    delivering products of the highest possible value. Scrum is:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Lightweight&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Simple to understand&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Extremely difficult to master&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Scrum is a process framework that has been used to manage complex product development since the early 1990s. Scrum is&#xD;
    not a process or a technique for building products; rather, it is a framework within which you can employ various&#xD;
    processes and techniques. Scrum makes clear the relative efficacy of your product management and development practices&#xD;
    so that you can improve.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Framework&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Scrum framework consists of Scrum Teams and their associated roles, events, artifacts, and rules. Each component&#xD;
    within the framework serves a specific purpose and is essential to Scrum’s success and usage.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Specific strategies for using the Scrum framework vary and are described elsewhere.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The rules of Scrum bind together the events, roles, and artifacts, governing the relationships and interaction between&#xD;
    them. The rules of Scrum are described throughout the body of this practice.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Roles&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/roles/scrum_team_8D8F2B3.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_O65KUOF6Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Scrum Team&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/roles/product_owner_10E7BD3.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_QcnRMOF5Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Product Owner&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/roles/development_team_2BE2D5BF.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_EChNoBC0EeGhfJHCQDJMKQ&quot;>Development Team&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/roles/scrum_master_357FCB70.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_Bw-twOF6Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Scrum Master&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Events&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Prescribed events are used in Scrum to create regularity and to minimize the need for meetings not defined in Scrum.&#xD;
    Scrum uses time-boxed events, such that every event has a maximum duration. This ensures an appropriate amount of time&#xD;
    is spent planning without allowing waste in the planning process.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Other than the Sprint itself, which is a container for all other events, each event in Scrum is a formal opportunity to&#xD;
    inspect and adapt something. These events are specifically designed to enable critical transparency and inspection.&#xD;
    Failure to include any of these events results in reduced transparency and is a lost opportunity to inspect and adapt.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/capabilitypatterns/sprint_C3956E4C.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_rsd8cw-NEeGvZJJrUZdBHA&quot;>Sprint&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
        href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/tasks/sprint_planning_meeting_9F0B8F28.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_4gCKAOF9Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Sprint Planning Meeting&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/tasks/daily_scrum_C8FB7908.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_oSM0AOF-Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Daily Scrum&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/tasks/sprint_review_8735340C.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_i_fkQOF-Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Sprint Review&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/tasks/sprint_retrospective_262A428.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_sKJ9AOF-Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Sprint Retrospective&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Artefacts&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Scrum’s artifacts represent work or value in various ways that are useful in providing transparency and opportunities&#xD;
    for inspection and adaptation. Artifacts defined by Scrum are specifically designed to maximize transparency of key&#xD;
    information needed to ensure Scrum Teams are successful in delivering a “Done” Increment.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/workproducts/product_backlog_68345C16.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_OZIPIOF8Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Product Backlog&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/workproducts/sprint_backlog_7A5B8A37.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;_Q5Ki8OF8Edyp34pwdTOSVQ&quot;>Sprint Backlog&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../practice.mgmt.scrum.base-sintef/workproducts/increment_69E6418C.html&quot;&#xD;
        guid=&quot;__uNYkPVgEdyMdecrgpMbRg&quot;>Increment&lt;/a>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Immutability of Scrum&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Scrum’s roles, artifacts, events, and rules are immutable and although implementing only parts of Scrum is possible,&#xD;
    the result is not Scrum. Scrum exists only in its entirety and functions well as a container for other techniques,&#xD;
    methodologies, and practices.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
